            + The historical phenomenon of colonization is one that stretches around the globe and across time. 
                \b Ancient and medieval colonialism was practiced by the Phoenicians, the Greeks, the Turks, and the Arabs. 
                \b Colonialism in the modern sense began with the "Age of Discovery", led by Portuguese, 
                \b and then by the Spanish exploration of the Americas, the coasts of Africa, Southwest Asia which is also known as the Middle East, India, and East Asia. 
                \b The Portuguese and Spanish empires were the first global empires because they were the first to stretch across different continents, 
                \b covering vast territories around the globe. 
                \b Between 1580 and 1640, the two empires were both ruled by the Spanish monarchs in personal union. 
                \b During the late 16th and 17th centuries, England, France and the Dutch Republic also established their own overseas empires, 
                \b in direct competition with one another.                
            + Some commentators identify three waves of European colonialism.[1]
            + The three main countries in the first wave of European colonialism were Portugal, Spain and the early Ottoman Empire.
                \b The Portuguese started the long age of European colonisation with the conquest of Ceuta, Morocco in 1415, 
                \b and the conquest and discovery of other African territories and islands, 
                \b this would also start the movement known as the Age of Discoveries. 
                \b The Ottomans conquered South Eastern Europe, the Middle East and much of Northern and Eastern Africa between 1359 and 1653 - 
                \b with the latter territories subjected to colonial occupation, rather than traditional territorial conquest. 
                \b The Spanish and Portuguese launched the colonisation of the Americas, basing their territorial claims on the Treaty of Tordesillas of 1494. 
                \b This treaty demarcated the respective spheres of influence of Spain and Portugal.
            + The expansion achieved by Spain and Portugal caught the attention of Britain, France and the Netherlands.
                \b The entrance of these three powers into the Caribbean and North America perpetuated European colonialism in these regions.
            + The second wave of European colonialism commenced with Britain's involvement in Asia in support of the British East India Company; 
                \b other countries such as France, Portugal and the Netherlands also had involvement in European expansion in Asia.
                \b The third wave ("New Imperialism") consisted of the Scramble for Africa regulated by the terms of the Berlin Conference of 1884-1885. 
                \b The conference effectively divided Africa among the European powers. 
                \b Vast regions of Africa came under the sway of Britain, France, Germany, Portugal, Belgium, Italy and Spain.
            + Gilmartin argues that these three waves of colonialism were linked to capitalism. 
                \b The first wave of European expansion involved exploring the world to find new revenue and perpetuating European feudalism. 
                \b The second wave focused on developing the mercantile capitalism system and the manufacturing industry in Europe. 
                \b The last wave of European colonialism solidified all capitalistic endeavours by providing new markets and raw materials.
            + As a result of these waves of European colonial expansion, 
                \b only following thirteen present-day independent countries escaped formal colonization by European powers: 
                \b Afghanistan, Bhutan, China, Iran, Japan, Liberia, Mongolia, Nepal, North Korea, Saudi Arabia, South Korea, 
                \b Thailand and Turkey as well as North Yemen, the former independent country which is now part of Yemen.

