                \b Alongside the formal control exerted over its own colonies, 
                \b Britain's dominant position in world trade meant that it effectively controlled access to many regions, 
                \b such as Asia, North America, Oceania, and Africa. 
                \b The British also, much to the dismay of other colonial empires, 
                \b helped the United States uphold the Monroe Doctrine which upheld its economic dominance in the Americas. 
                \b British merchants, shippers and bankers had such an overwhelming advantage over those of other empires 
                \b that in addition to its colonies it had an informal empire.

